      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        China‚Äôs response to scamdemic
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: China has selectively intervened in Southeast Asia‚Äôs scam crisis to protect its borders and global image.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        China's response to Southeast Asia's online scam is primarily <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-may-25-analysis-h1-7-driven-by-self-interest" target="_blank">driven by self-interest</a> rather than a clear foreign policy. Although China officially supports non-interference, it has intervened selectively in Myanmar, Cambodia, and Laos. This is based on threats to its national interests, like border stability, citizen safety, and the reputation of the Chinese state and its Belt and Road Initiative.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The level of intervention varies per country. In Myanmar, China has acted firmly due to risks to border security and vital infrastructure, like gas pipelines. It has even engaged with rebel groups in the area. In Cambodia, intervention increased when the government showed a willingness to cooperate. The stakes are higher in these countries. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        China has mostly stayed out of areas with less immediate interest, such as Yatai New City and Laos' Golden Triangle Special Economic Zone. While researchers argue that China asserts to follow through with its principle of non-interference, its actions suggest a more pragmatic approach. It prioritizes judicial and cooperative methods of intervention. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Since the pandemic, Southeast Asia has become a hotspot for online scamming operations, primarily driven by Chinese transnational criminal syndicates. These scams have defrauded a large sum of currency and trafficked many into exploitative ‚Äúscam centers‚Äù under the guise of legitimate jobs. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
