          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
    Why India is losing Bangladesh to China?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/india-bangladesh-strained-relations-2025.jpg" alt="India-Bangladesh ties have unraveled into mutual suspicion, strategic maneuvering, and a dangerous blame game" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>India-Bangladesh ties have unraveled into mutual suspicion, strategic maneuvering, and a dangerous blame game.</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        Since the ousting of Bangladesh‚Äôs PM, Sheikh Hasina, the relationship between India and Bangladesh has reached a low point. India‚Äôs <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-may-25-foundations-h1-14-troubles-with-bangladesh" target="_blank">troubles with Bangladesh</a> stem from New Delhi‚Äôs unwavering support for Hasina‚Äôs authoritarian regime and the rise of Hindu nationalism under Indian PM Narendra Modi. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          By prioritizing short-term security interests and domestic politics over democratic values, India alienated the Bangladeshi public. Meanwhile, Indian media framed Bangladesh‚Äôs pivot as a conspiracy orchestrated by China and Pakistan. This alienated the Bangladeshi people and their leadership, who have grown closer to China and Pakistan. </p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        India has also failed to recognize long-standing issues, including the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-may-25-foundations-h1-15-teesta-river-sharing" target="_blank">Teesta river sharing</a> dispute, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-may-25-foundations-h1-16-caa-nrc-controversies" target="_blank">CAA-NRC controversies</a>, and killings of Bangladeshi civilians along the India-Bangladesh border. While the Indian leaders preach a ‚Äúneighborhood first‚Äù policy, many in Bangladesh feel India prioritizes domestic political gains, particularly in West Bengal.</p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Meanwhile, China has become one of Bangladesh‚Äôs largest trading partners and a major source of infrastructure funding under the Belt and Road Initiative. While India has a strong cultural influence, China has been aggressively building its soft power through scholarships, language centers, and media engagement. China‚Äôs ‚Äúnon-interference‚Äù approach makes China a more palatable partner for some in Dhaka.</p>
       </mj-text>
